<span id="freeTextContainer622975738067067238">&quot;Why I am Not a Muslim&quot; is probably one of the highlights of religion criticism. It is very analytical and larded with secondary literature, but the author achieves his goal: to fully dissect Islam (and some bits of Christianity and Judaism). Its relevance today cannot be ignored and some sections are disturbing indeed (namely the real implication of jihad and how an Islamic state views itself and the other part of the world). Although chapters 10 &amp; 11 appear somewhat tedious, others (like on Ar</span>
  <span id="freeText622975738067067238" style="display:none">"Why I am Not a Muslim" is probably one of the highlights of religion criticism. It is very analytical and larded with secondary literature, but the author achieves his goal: to fully dissect Islam (and some bits of Christianity and Judaism). Its relevance today cannot be ignored and some sections are disturbing indeed (namely the real implication of jihad and how an Islamic state views itself and the other part of the world). Although chapters 10 &amp; 11 appear somewhat tedious, others (like on Arab imperialism and the position of women) make up for that, and the book as a whole never fails in holding one's interest. </span>
  <a data-text-id="622975738067067238" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
